      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry insight\n\nCu²⁺'s dominance is no surprise — its **d⁹ electronic configuration** gives it Jahn–Teller flexibility, allowing it to adopt a wide range of coordination geometries (square planar, tetragonal, octahedral). Its **borderline hard–soft character** means it binds effectively to N-, O-, and S-donor ligands alike, making it the most versatile and most-studied metal ion in solution equilibrium chemistry. The top five are all divalent first-row transition metals (plus Cd²⁺), reflecting the historical focus of coordination chemistry on these biogeochemically important ions.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
